You can achieve this by iterating through the categories in the wxArrayString and for each category, counting the number of elements in the corresponding array using the size() function. You can then create a new wxArrayString with the desired format.

Here's an example function that demonstrates this:

```cpp
wxArrayString GetCategoryCountArray(const wxArrayString& categories, const wxArrayString& elements) {
    wxArrayString categoryCountArray;

    for (const wxString& category : categories) {
        size_t count = 0;

        for (const wxString& element : elements) {
            if (element == category)
                count++;
        }

        wxString categoryCountString = wxString::Format("[%d] %s", count, category);
        categoryCountArray.Add(categoryCountString);
    }

    return categoryCountArray;
}
```

You can then use this function like this:

```cpp
wxArrayString categories;
categories.Add("Category1");
categories.Add("Category2");
categories.Add("Category3");

wxArrayString elements;
elements.Add("Category1");
elements.Add("Category2");
elements.Add("Category3");
elements.Add("Category1");
elements.Add("Category2");

wxArrayString categoryCountArray = GetCategoryCountArray(categories, elements);

for (const wxString& categoryCount : categoryCountArray) {
    wxString countCategory;
    countCategory << categoryCount << "\n";
    // do something with countCategory
}
```

This will output:

```
[2] Category1
[2] Category2
[1] Category3
```

Here, the count represents the number of occurrences of each category in the elements array.

